<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-06-27T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-06-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="185" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d185">
                                <note rend="inline" type="source">462.00R296/4190</note>
                                <head><hi rend="italic">The Polish Chargé</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Sokolowski</hi></persName>)
                                        <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary
                                            of State</gloss></hi></head>
                                <p>The Chargé d’Affaires ad interim of Poland presents his
                                    compliments to the Acting Secretary of State, and referring to
                                    his enquiry of June 25, 1931,<note n="25" xml:id="d185fn25">Not
                                        found in Department files.</note> as to the attitude of the
                                    Polish Government towards the proposal of President Hoover
                                    published in the general press on June 20th and 21st, has the
                                    honor to inform him that the Polish Government welcomes with the
                                    highest appreciation the noble initiative of President Hoover,
                                    in the belief that it will be coincident with a general
                                    political relaxation, and regards such initiative as an
                                    important step towards the stabilization of Peace.</p>
                                <closer>
                                    <dateline rendition="#left">
                                        <placeName>
                                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-06-27">June 27, 1931</date>.</dateline>
                                </closer>
                                <postscript>
                                    <p>No. 168/T/31</p>
                                </postscript>
                            </div>
